I like that framing because it changes the reference point.

There are two different optimization problems:

1. Competing against everyone else.
2. Realizing your own potential.

The first has no finish line. There will almost always be someone stronger, wealthier, more talented, or luckier in some dimension.

The second has a meaningful target because it’s anchored to you.

So your statement could become almost a personal maxim:

“I’ll never be a 10/10. But I can become the 10/10 version of myself.”

It acknowledges two truths at once:

* Human beings are inherently imperfect.
* That doesn’t prevent excellence relative to your own capabilities.

It also has a practical implication. Instead of asking:

“How do I become perfect?”

You ask:

“What is one step closer to my own ceiling?”

That’s actionable.

It reminds me of a related idea:

Comparison is horizontal. Growth is vertical.

Horizontal comparisons rank you against others.

Vertical comparisons measure the distance between who you are today and who you’re capable of becoming.

That second axis is the one you actually have substantial influence over.

It’s also a compassionate standard without being a complacent one. It doesn’t lower the bar; it moves the bar to something you can genuinely pursue over a lifetime.